121289
). Papua New Guinea : Collingwood Bay (AM C. 18891 ).

Sowerby (1855 , 1866 ) erroneously gave the locality as ‘ Philippines and Borneo’ (as
Cerithium kieneri
).

Remarks. The shell shows considerable regional variation. Specimens from Merauke, S New Guinea , and one from the nearby Torres Strait (
Fig. 10 J, N–P
) show increased numbers of fine axial ribs on the spire (these were named
C. multicostata
Schepman, 1919
). Shells from elsewhere in New Guinea are slender and delicate, but again have fine and sometimes numerous axial ribs (
Fig. 10 E, F
). Shells from E Queensland are large, with coarse sculpture (
Fig. 10 H, I, K–M
). Those from the Gulf of Carpentaria are thick and pale. In the Northern Territory the whorls are slightly compressed vertically to produce a broader shell (
Fig. 10 A–D
). COI sequence data reveal a deep division between two specimens from Darwin and one from the Torres Strait (uncorrected pairwise distance = 0.072 ) and phylogenetic analysis does not give significant support to the monophyly of all three (
Reid et al . 2013
;
Fig. 1
). However, molecular sampling is so far too limited to determine whether this division corresponds in any way with the observed pattern of morphological variation. The distribution appears to be continuous around the northern coast of Australia , so does not suggest any geographical separation between eastern and western populations. Nevertheless, a pattern of eastern and western genetic differentiation (both intra- and inter-specific) across northern Australia is common in marine organisms and has been explained by isolation during glacial low sea-level stands (
Reid et al . 2006
, 2010 ). Further investigation is required of genetic structure and possible speciation in
C. anticipata
.
